{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"041f2f0b-ab56-466d-b83f-014be9a1c9d1","content":"No worries — I don't need to see the project to answer this. Here's how to configure it:\n\nCreate (or edit) `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for MCP).\n- **`command` / `args`** — runs `dotnet run --project ...`, so your server starts on demand.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable and drop the `args`.\n\nMake sure your MCP server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK with stdio transport). Any logging should go to **stderr**, not stdout, to avoid corrupting the protocol stream.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4f45a5e3-5d6d-4d12-a09d-43ace80bb4ce","outputTokens":275,"requestId":"C03D:AA16B:1D2E6FC:20CBD34:6A07C30B"},"id":"4c6d01f9-dd57-4385-8f91-525e08ba4061","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:27.720Z","parentId":"b64633e0-6e09-4bcf-a770-954591a71f8b"}
